
[1]espy

   ESPY',v.t. [L. specio.]

   1. To see at a distance; to have the first sight of a thing remove.
   Seamen espy land as they approach it.

   2. To see or discover something intended to be hid, or in a degree
   concealed and not very visible; as, to espy a man in a crowd, or a
   thief in a wood.

   3. To discover unexpectedly.

   As one of them opened his sack, he espied his money. Gen.42.

   4. To inspect narrowly; to examine and make discoveries.

   Moses sent me to espy out the land, and I brought him word again. Josh.
   14.

           ESPY', v.i. To look narrowly; to look about; to watch.

   Stand by the way and espy. Jer.48.

               [This word is often pronounced spy, which see.]

                          ESPY', n. A spy; a scout.
